    <Entry>
      <ID>261</ID>
      <DefaultText>"You don't remember? I guess that's why you made me." He chuckles. Then his face grows serious. "You never tried to merge your consciousness with hers. After researching it for a while, we discovered that doing so would snuff out your personality - you weren't content with me being the only one of us left. So we rejected that option and kept searching for some other way."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>262</ID>
      <DefaultText>He shakes his head. "I'm afraid we can't. You rejected it before we could implement any kind of experiment. We'd need some kind of psychic substrate for your consciousness and hers to reside in simultaneously. Then we'd need a catalyst of some kind to create the resonance that would merge you with her. It's certainly possible, given time, but the Sorrow's at our doorstep!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>263</ID>
      <DefaultText>Although your body is gone, your awareness somehow remains *here*, in the laboratory. The spectral adviser is gone, and the Sorrow breaks through the last defenses and up through the hatch. Its tendrils flay the laboratory all around it. The chest and diamond are cut to ribbons. The chamber disintegrates in a ball of purple flame, and the last thing you see as your mind fades from this body is the face of the young girl, melting and boiling into ash.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>264</ID>
      <DefaultText>[DEBUG] Exit mere.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>265</ID>
      <DefaultText>[DEBUG] Exit mere with consciousness-merging knowledge.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>266</ID>
      <DefaultText>The transdimensional wall projector has already been activated, though there's no indication of whether the wall is holding or not.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>267</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Absolutely not." He shakes his head emphatically. "I've already set the failsafe to teleport her instead of you - which, for the record, I think is a *bad* idea. But there's no way I'm killing us all right now, no matter how scared you are."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
